  <content>
    <title>Performance Domains Overview</title>
    <summary>PMBoK 7 defines eight interconnected performance domains — Stakeholder, Team, Development Approach, Planning, Project Work, Delivery, Measurement, Uncertainty — that together enable successful project delivery. Domains are ongoing concurrent concerns, not sequential phases. The overview serves as a router and assessment harness: triage which domains need active management, select the relevant detailed methodologies, and score each domain green/yellow/red at project gates.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Process-based PM can feel mechanical and disconnected from outcomes. Teams follow steps without understanding value. Performance domains shift focus from activities to results: what must be true for the project to succeed, not what process must be followed. The domain interaction matrix (poor Stakeholder → Team + Delivery suffer) provides leading indicators rather than lagging post-mortems.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Onboarding a new project: triage which of the 8 PMBOK7 domains need active management on this engagement.</item>
        <item>Periodic project health checks where you score each domain green/yellow/red and decide where to spend management attention.</item>
        <item>Tailoring an engagement: deciding which methodologies (RACI, EVM, risk register, communication plan) to instantiate vs skip based on domain weight.</item>
        <item>Mapping legacy-PMBOK6 process documentation onto the PMBOK7 outcome-based view during cert prep or audit.</item>
        <item>Routing a multi-methodology agent: a router that picks the right detailed methodology (scope-management, schedule-development, EVM, etc.) given a project question.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-task work where a checklist suffices; the framework adds overhead without changing decisions.</item>
        <item>Pure scrum teams for whom Scrum Guide already defines roles, ceremonies and metrics — domains and Scrum aren't contradictory but redundant overlay creates confusion.</item>
        <item>Operations / BAU work that is not a project (no defined start/end, no unique outcome).</item>
        <item>Low-stakes internal work where domain assessment cost &gt; project cost.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Eight PMBoK 7 Performance Domains">
      <section name="1. Stakeholder">
        <p>Purpose: effectively engage stakeholders throughout the project. Outcomes: stakeholders identified and understood, engagement strategies developed, stakeholders actively involved, satisfaction achieved. Related methodologies: stakeholder-register, stakeholder-engagement.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="2. Team">
        <p>Purpose: establish and maintain a high-performing project team. Outcomes: shared ownership, collaborative environment, continuous development, distributed leadership. Related methodologies: raci-matrix, team-development, communications-management.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="3. Development Approach">
        <p>Purpose: select and maintain the optimal delivery approach. Outcomes: approach aligned with project needs, continuous improvement incorporated. Approach options: Predictive (clear requirements, low uncertainty), Iterative (need to refine solution), Incremental (deliver partial value early), Agile (high uncertainty, need flexibility), Hybrid (mixed characteristics). Related methodologies: agile-hybrid-approaches.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="4. Planning">
        <p>Purpose: plan how project work will be done. Outcomes: organised scope, realistic schedule and budget, resource plans. Related methodologies: work-breakdown-structure, schedule-development, cost-estimation, scope-management.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="5. Project Work">
        <p>Purpose: establish processes and perform work efficiently. Outcomes: efficient processes, appropriate communication, resources managed, procurements handled. Related methodologies: change-control, procurement-management.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="6. Delivery">
        <p>Purpose: deliver value and outcomes that stakeholders accept. Outcomes: scope completed, quality met, benefits realised. Related methodologies: quality-management, benefits-realization, project-closure.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="7. Measurement">
        <p>Purpose: assess project performance and take action. Outcomes: reliable decision information, timely data, performance forecasts. Related methodologies: earned-value-management, lessons-learned.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="8. Uncertainty">
        <p>Purpose: address uncertainty and risk proactively. Outcomes: threats reduced, opportunities captured, reserves appropriate. Related methodologies: risk-register, risk-management.</p>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="Domain Interaction Matrix">
      <p>When a domain struggles, these others are typically affected:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Stakeholder weak → Team, Delivery, Measurement suffer (misaligned expectations propagate)</item>
        <item>Team weak → Project Work, Delivery suffer (execution degrades)</item>
        <item>Development Approach wrong → Planning, Project Work, Delivery suffer (wrong tools for the work)</item>
        <item>Planning weak → Project Work, Delivery, Measurement suffer (no baseline to measure against)</item>
        <item>Project Work weak → Delivery, Measurement suffer (output quality degrades)</item>
        <item>Delivery weak → Stakeholder, Measurement suffer (value not visible)</item>
        <item>Measurement weak → all domains suffer (no visibility into what is wrong)</item>
        <item>Uncertainty weak → all domains suffer (unmanaged risks materialise unpredictably)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Assessment and Governance Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Re-assess domains at every project gate (kickoff, mid-point, pre-launch, close), not weekly; weekly drives status theatre.</statement>
        <rationale>Domain assessment is a strategic tool; overuse dilutes its signal and creates reporting overhead without changing PM decisions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Start every status report with the two weakest domains; do not rotate through all 8.</statement>
        <rationale>Focus on the weakest domains drives action; rotating through all eight creates the illusion of coverage without improving anything.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>The Uncertainty domain requires an active risk register to score green; absence of a register means automatic red.</statement>
        <rationale>Uncertainty is most often under-resourced; requiring a concrete artefact prevents superficial compliance.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Domains are NOT phases; never write "Stakeholder phase complete" or "Team phase done".</statement>
        <rationale>Domains are ongoing concurrent concerns that persist for the entire project; "complete" misrepresents the nature of domain management.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>When dropping a domain for a low-stakes project, drop the entire domain, not partial methodologies; "light EVM" is usually fake EVM.</statement>
        <rationale>Half-applied methodologies consume overhead without delivering the discipline benefits; commit or skip explicitly.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Limitations and Gotchas">
      <p>"Outcomes not processes" sounds clean but PMBOK7 still ships ~50 process artefacts in the Standard for Project Management; agents trained on PMBOK6 mix the two.</p>
      <p>Domain interactions are described qualitatively; an agent cannot quantitatively trade Stakeholder vs Measurement attention without a separate decision model.</p>
      <p>Performance Domains are auditing primitives, not delivery primitives — you cannot "do" the Stakeholder Domain, only do stakeholder engagement and assess against the domain.</p>
      <p>Many real LLM outputs collapse the 8 domains back into the old 5 process groups (Initiate / Plan / Execute / M&amp;C / Close); this is a regression.</p>
      <p>The framework intentionally avoids prescribing tools — agents tend to invent processes to fill the gap, drifting back to PMBOK6.</p>
      <p>2026 cert weights shift Business Environment from 8% to 26% (see pm-certification-changes-2026); training data still reflects old weights.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow Patterns">
      <p>Use the overview as a router and assessment harness, not as an executable methodology. A domain-router agent reads the user's project question, classifies it into one or more of the 8 domains, and dispatches to the detailed methodology agents (scope-management, EVM, risk-management, etc.). A separate domain-assessor agent scores each domain green/yellow/red weekly using objective inputs (sprint metrics, risk register count, stakeholder satisfaction survey) and surfaces the weakest two domains to the human PM. Humans own the strategic call on where to invest attention.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents:</p>
      <list>
        <item>domain-router — classify input → 1-3 of {stakeholder, team, dev-approach, planning, project-work, delivery, measurement, uncertainty}; emit confidence + rationale.</item>
        <item>domain-assessor — input: project artefacts, output: per-domain RAG status with cited evidence.</item>
        <item>tailoring-advisor — input: project context (size, risk, regulated?) → which detailed methodologies to enable.</item>
        <item>faion-pm-agent (existing skill router) — already routes to detailed PM methodologies.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Prompt pattern:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[System: You are the PMBOK7 Performance Domains classifier.
Domains: stakeholder, team, dev-approach, planning, project-work,
         delivery, measurement, uncertainty.

Input: <project question or status item>
Output JSON:
{ "primary_domain": "<one>",
  "secondary_domains": ["<...>"],
  "rationale": "<one sentence>",
  "recommended_methodologies": ["scope-management", ...],
  "confidence": 0.0-1.0 }

If the input is operational (not project work), return
{"out_of_scope": true, "reason": "..."}]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="Anti-Patterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Collapsing the 8 domains back into the old 5 process groups (Initiate/Plan/Execute/M&amp;C/Close).</description>
        <reason>This is a PMBoK 6 regression; domains are outcome-based auditing primitives, not sequential phases.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Asking an LLM "is this domain healthy?" without providing evidence artefacts or metrics.</description>
        <reason>Without inputs, the agent produces generic prose that does not reflect actual project health; always feed evidence and require citations.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="CLI Tools and Services">
      <p>CLI tools for domain assessment and cross-project analysis:</p>
      <list>
        <item>gh project / jira-cli — Pull project artefacts that feed domain assessment; https://cli.github.com/, https://github.com/ankitpokhrel/jira-cli</item>
        <item>pandas / duckdb — Aggregate cross-domain metrics (sprint velocity, EVM, risk count) into a single dashboard; https://duckdb.org/</item>
        <item>mermaid-cli — Render the 8-domain interaction map for status reports; https://github.com/mermaid-js/mermaid-cli</item>
        <item>gpt-cli / claude — Run the router agent locally over a backlog of items</item>
        <item>streamlit — Build a domain RAG dashboard from CSV/JSON; https://streamlit.io/</item>
      </list>
      <p>Services and platforms for portfolio and domain-level governance:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Smartsheet PMO (SaaS) — Domain-tagged work portfolio; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Monday.com (SaaS) — Custom statuses for domain RAG; GraphQL API; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Notion / Confluence (SaaS) — Where the PMBOK7 tailoring doc lives; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Asana Portfolios (SaaS) — Cross-project domain rollup; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Jira + Atlas (SaaS) — Atlas gives portfolio-level domain status; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>ClickUp Goals (SaaS) — Tie outcomes to delivery domain; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>OnePager Pro (SaaS) — One-page exec status by domain; limited agent support</item>
        <item>ProjectManager.com (SaaS) — PMBOK-aligned PMO tooling; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Re-assess domains at every project gate (kickoff, mid-point, pre-launch, close), not weekly — weekly drives status-theatre.</item>
        <item>Start every status report with the two weakest domains; do not rotate through all 8 — focus drives action.</item>
        <item>Map your existing artefacts (RACI, risk register, EVM dashboard) onto domains explicitly so the framework augments, not replaces, your toolkit.</item>
        <item>When tailoring, drop entire domains, not partial methodologies. "Light EVM" is usually fake EVM. Either commit or skip.</item>
        <item>The Uncertainty domain is most often under-resourced; require an active risk register or downgrade to red.</item>
        <item>Use the domain interaction matrix (e.g., poor Stakeholder → Team + Delivery suffer) as the leading indicator; do not wait for downstream domains to slip.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Domain naming is not stable: "Project Work" is sometimes labelled "Execution"; agents trained on draft PMBOK7 use both. Pin canonical names in the prompt.</item>
        <item>LLMs collapse "Development Approach" into "Methodology" and lose the distinction between hybrid/iterative/incremental — feed the table explicitly.</item>
        <item>Asking an LLM "is this domain healthy?" without inputs returns generic prose. Always feed evidence (artefact links, metrics) and require citations.</item>
        <item>The framework is principle-based; agents over-rotate to checklists. Bias prompts toward "what outcome is at risk?" not "did we follow process?"</item>
        <item>2026 exam alignment shifts weights toward Business Environment (Value Delivery, Governance, Sustainability); agents using pre-2026 training will under-emphasise these.</item>
        <item>Cross-domain double-counting: the same status item often hits Stakeholder + Communication + Delivery; require the router to pick a primary and list secondaries explicitly.</item>
        <item>Domains are NOT phases. Agents that emit "Stakeholder phase complete" need correction.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/domain-assessment.md" purpose="Eight-row domain health assessment template with RAG status, issues, and actions" />
    </templates>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.pmi.org/pmbok-guide-standards" />
